{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-06-11T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"From above, the lake's smooth surface contrasts sharply with the rugged ground surrounding it. Hnausapollur crater lake—also known as Bláhylur—lies in the heart of Fjallabak Nature Reserve, a remote area of Iceland's highlands shaped more by volcanic activity than by human settlement. The crater formed when magma met groundwater, triggering an explosion that carved out the circular basin visible today.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Hnausapollur_EN-US2080493040_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Hnausapollur_EN-US2080493040_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"A splash of blue","Title":"Hnausapollur volcanic crater lake, Fjallabak Nature Reserve, Landmannalaugar, Iceland","Copyright":"© Juan Maria Coy Vergara/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/64.055313,-19.031654/5?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=64.055313,-19.031654;S9;Hnausapollur, Iceland&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260610_Hnausapollur\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Hnausapollur+Iceland&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260610_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260610_Hnausapollur"},"Ssd":"20260610","Name":"Hnausapollur","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"2080493040","FullDateString":"Jun 10, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Vernazza is a small seaside town in Cinque Terre, in Italy's Liguria region. Built around the area's only natural harbor, it has long been tied to the sea. First recorded in 1080 as a fortified settlement and maritime base, it later became part of the Republic of Genoa's coastal defenses. To this day, the village preserves its past in the ruins of Doria Castle and the watchtowers overlooking the bay. At the water's edge stands the Church of Santa Margherita d'Antiochia, first mentioned in 1318 and expanded in later centuries, with a bell tower overlooking the port. Above the houses and narrow lanes, steep terraces support vineyards and olive groves, shaped by generations of stonework in a landscape protected within Cinque Terre National Park, part of a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Picture an aperitivo here: a glass of local white wine, the harbor in view, and Ligurian favorites like focaccia and basil pesto—basically a postcard you can taste.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.CTNPVernazza_EN-US1571456265_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.CTNPVernazza_EN-US1571456265_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Taste the sunset","Title":"Vernazza, Cinque Terre, Liguria, Italy","Copyright":"© Kelly Cheng/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/44.135512,9.681952/8?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=44.135512,9.681952;S9;Vernazza, Liguria, Italy&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260609_CTNPVernazza\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Vernazza+Cinque+Terre+Liguria+Italy&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260609_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260609_CTNPVernazza"},"Ssd":"20260609","Name":"CTNPVernazza","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"1571456265","FullDateString":"Jun 9, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Today is World Oceans Day, so follow the lead of a creature that goes wherever the water takes it. Want to spot a lion's mane jellyfish? Look in cold northern seas. Its bell is split into eight lobes, and beneath it hang long tentacles and oral arms. As it drifts with the current, stinging cells snare plankton and small fish. For humans, the sting can be painful. Reactions vary, and even a washed-up tentacle can still hurt. The rule is simple: admire it, then leave it alone. Some lion's manes in Arctic waters have bells more than 6 feet across, but most sightings are smaller animals near shore after storms or strong currents.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Cyanea_EN-US1146473249_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Cyanea_EN-US1146473249_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Drift with the current","Title":"Lion's mane jellyfish swimming in the ocean","Copyright":"© Alexander Semenov Images/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"Though mostly water, the lion's mane jellyfish can reach 120 feet in length—surpassing even the blue whale.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260608_Cyanea\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=World+Oceans+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260608_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260608_Cyanea"},"Ssd":"20260608","Name":"Cyanea","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"1146473249","FullDateString":"Jun 8, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Since opening its doors in 1976, the Atlanta Botanical Garden has proven that beauty can be organized. Beds are planned, labels are placed, and every plant has a job. 'To have a garden is not as easy as it seems; it is just as difficult as governing a kingdom.' Nobel Prize-winning German author Hermann Hesse had a point.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.GardenAtlanta_EN-US2319128074_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.GardenAtlanta_EN-US2319128074_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":false},"Headline":"Plant your kingdom","Title":"Atlanta Botanical Garden, Atlanta, Georgia","Copyright":"© Marcus E Jones/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"Originating in ancient Persia, 'paradise' meant a walled garden, a meaning carried through Greek 'paradeisos' to Latin 'paradisus.'","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260607_GardenAtlanta\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=National+Garden+Week&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260607_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260607_GardenAtlanta"},"Ssd":"20260607","Name":"GardenAtlanta","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"2319128074","FullDateString":"Jun 7, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"If your screen time has been winning lately, today is a good time to change that—we suggest hiking. National Trails Day, created in 1993 by the American Hiking Society, nudges people toward exploring trails.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.HikingNatchez_EN-US0663065299_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.HikingNatchez_EN-US0663065299_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Wander often, wonder more","Title":"Natchez Trace Parkway, Tupelo, Mississippi, USA","Copyright":"© The best photo is earned/Getty Images Plus","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/31.54333,-91.38306/6?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=31.54333,-91.38306;S9;Natchez Trace Parkway, Tupelo, Mississippi&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260606_HikingNatchez\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=National+Trails+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260606_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260606_HikingNatchez"},"Ssd":"20260606","Name":"HikingNatchez","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"0663065299","FullDateString":"Jun 6, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"If nature had a 'do not disturb' sign, it would hang over Sarek National Park, often called 'the last European wilderness.' On World Environment Day, this remote corner of Swedish Lapland reminds us what the planet looks like when humans take a step back—and let the wild take the lead.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.WedLapland_EN-US9813120088_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.WedLapland_EN-US9813120088_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"The quiet power of an unclaimed world","Title":"View from Skierffe Mountain over the Rapadalen river delta, Sarek National Park, Laponia, Lapland, Sweden","Copyright":"© Robert Haasmann/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/67.28834,17.66914/5?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=67.28834,17.66914;S9;Sarek National Park, Laponia, Lapland, Sweden&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260605_WedLapland\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=World+Environment+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260605_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260605_WedLapland"},"Ssd":"20260605","Name":"WedLapland","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"9813120088","FullDateString":"Jun 5, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Poetic name, poetic appearance. Meet the snowy egret, whose all-white plumage and bright yellow 'slippers' on black legs give it a striking look. Once nearly wiped out by demand for its delicate breeding-season feathers—soft, lacy plumes prized for fashionable hats—conservation efforts saved its plumage.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PreeningEgret_EN-US9350488148_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PreeningEgret_EN-US9350488148_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Fancy feathers","Title":"Snowy egret preening, central Florida, USA","Copyright":"© Donald M. Jones/Minden Pictures","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"Snowy egrets often feed alongside herons, benefiting from the movement that stirs hidden prey into view.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260604_PreeningEgret\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=snowy+egret&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260604_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260604_PreeningEgret"},"Ssd":"20260604","Name":"PreeningEgret","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"9350488148","FullDateString":"Jun 4, 2026"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Follow the glowing ribbon of switchbacks and you'll find one of Switzerland's most legendary drives: Tremola Road, the historic southern approach to the Saint Gotthard Pass, above Airolo. Built in the early 1800s and largely shaped by a 1951 reconstruction, this route is celebrated as Switzerland's longest monument to historic road construction. Its showstopper stretch climbs about 980 feet in just 2.5 miles, curling through 24 named hairpin bends on granite cobblestones, with sturdy retaining walls edging the way. Overall, it runs about 7 miles and features 37 bends in total. Take it slow—every curve feels like a step back in time, trading speed for sweeping mountain scenery and big views toward the upper Leventina Valley. Whether you're driving, cycling, or pulling over for photos, look for the Grand Tour of Switzerland photo spot framing those iconic zigzags.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.TremolaRoad_EN-US6212254886_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.TremolaRoad_EN-US6212254886_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Twist your way up","Title":"Tremola Road on the Saint Gotthard Pass in Airolo, Switzerland","Copyright":"© Sandro Bisaro/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/46.557487,8.562773/10?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=46.557487,8.562773;S9;Saint Gotthard Pass, Airolo, Switzerland&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260617_TremolaRoad\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Tremola+Road&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260617_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260617_TremolaRoad"},"Ssd":"20260617","Name":"TremolaRoad","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"6212254886","FullDateString":"Jun 17, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Sea Turtle Day highlights some of the ocean's most ancient mariners—reptiles that have existed for over 100 million years. Observed each year on June 16, it raises awareness of their ecological importance and the growing threats they face. Sea turtles play a vital role in maintaining healthy seagrass beds and coral reefs, ecosystems that support diverse marine life. Long migrations between feeding and nesting areas are central to their life cycle. Despite their resilience, all species are threatened by habitat loss, plastic pollution, climate change, and accidental capture in fishing gear.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SevenMileTurtle_EN-US6164934763_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SevenMileTurtle_EN-US6164934763_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Nature's reef keepers","Title":"Hawksbill sea turtle pair near Seven Mile Beach, Grand Cayman, Cayman Islands","Copyright":"© Alex Mustard/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"The temperature of the sand where sea turtle eggs incubate determines whether the hatchlings are male or female.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260616_SevenMileTurtle\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=World+Sea+Turtle+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260616_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260616_SevenMileTurtle"},"Ssd":"20260616","Name":"SevenMileTurtle","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"6164934763","FullDateString":"Jun 16, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"These mountains were shaped over time—and June 15, 1934, helped protect them. That's when the Great Smoky Mountains National Park was established in Tennessee and North Carolina. Covering over 522,000 acres, the park takes its name from the natural smoky haze drifting over its ridgelines. Part of the Appalachian Mountains, these peaks are over 300 million years old.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ParkEstd_EN-US6114949122_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ParkEstd_EN-US6114949122_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Aged to scenic perfection","Title":"Great Smoky Mountains National Park, Tennessee","Copyright":"© Mint Images/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/35.613045,-83.553131/7?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=35.613045,-83.553131;S9;Great Smoky Mountains National Park, Tennessee&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260615_ParkEstd\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Great+Smoky+Mountains+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260615_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260615_ParkEstd"},"Ssd":"20260615","Name":"ParkEstd","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"6114949122","FullDateString":"Jun 15, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"On June 14, the stars align—and not just figuratively. They line up on a piece of fabric that has seen battles, protests, and backyard barbecues. Flag Day marks the 1777 decision by the Second Continental Congress to adopt the national flag, but the story goes beyond stitches and stripes.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.FlagsMonument_EN-US6034154869_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.FlagsMonument_EN-US6034154869_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"History flies high","Title":"US flags surrounding the Washington Monument, Washington, DC","Copyright":"© Orhan Cam/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/38.889477,-77.03508/12?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=38.889477,-77.03508;S9;Washington Monument, Washington, District of Columbia&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260614_FlagsMonument\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=US+Flag+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260614_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260614_FlagsMonument"},"Ssd":"20260614","Name":"FlagsMonument","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"6034154869","FullDateString":"Jun 14, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Layered ridges stretch across Badlands National Park in South Dakota. Their bands of pink, gray, and gold shift with the light as eroded peaks and valleys come into view. Wind and water continue to shape this terrain, steadily wearing away soft sedimentary rock and exposing millions of years of Earth's history in layers formed by ancient rivers, volcanic ash, and periods when shallow seas covered the region.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BadSunset_EN-US5981956630_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BadSunset_EN-US5981956630_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Layers of change","Title":"Sunset in Badlands National Park, South Dakota, USA","Copyright":"© Troy Harrison/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/43.85538,-102.339666/5?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=43.85538,-102.339666;S9;Badlands National Park, South Dakota&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260613_BadSunset\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Badlands+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260613_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260613_BadSunset"},"Ssd":"20260613","Name":"BadSunset","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"5981956630","FullDateString":"Jun 13, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"A streak of color glides past a blur of wildflowers as a European bee-eater cuts through the air. Turquoise, gold, and chestnut shimmer across its wings as it hunts in flight, snatching insects midair with swift turns. Bees and wasps are among its favored prey, and the bird often removes the stinger before feeding—a behavior that reduces the risk of injury.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SpainBeeEater_EN-US5920719155_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SpainBeeEater_EN-US5920719155_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"A flash in flight","Title":"European bee-eater, Sierra de Grazalema Natural Park, Cádiz, Spain","Copyright":"© Andres M. Dominguez/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/36.74794,-5.371703/6?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=36.74794,-5.371703;S9;Sierra de Grazalema Natural Park, Cádiz, Spain&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260612_SpainBeeEater\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=European+bee-eater&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260612_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260612_SpainBeeEater"},"Ssd":"20260612","Name":"SpainBeeEater","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"5920719155","FullDateString":"Jun 12, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Tucked away beneath steep cliffs near Cabo da Roca, the westernmost point of mainland Europe, Praia da Ursa feels like the edge of the continent. Reached by a narrow, rugged trail, this secluded beach along Portugal's Atlantic coast is shaped largely by wind, stone, and powerful waves. When the tide recedes, the shoreline briefly widens. Smooth rocks emerge, and with them, small signs of life. Limpets cling tightly to the exposed stone, holding fast where the ocean usually breaks.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Limpets_EN-US1055673545_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Limpets_EN-US1055673545_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Quiet strength","Title":"Limpets exposed at low tide on the coast of Praia da Ursa, Portugal","Copyright":"© Theo Bosboom/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/38.790765,-